Express.js – Complete Function Reference
1. express() Function
What it is

The main function of Express.

Creates an Express application instance.

Syntax
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

Purpose

Initializes the Express server

Used to define routes, middleware, and server settings

Example
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Hello Express');
});

app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log('Server running on port 3000');
});

Key Points

Returns an app object

Without express(), no server can be created

2. express.raw() Function
What it is

Built-in middleware

Parses incoming requests with raw binary data

Syntax
express.raw(options)

Use Case

When handling binary data

Used in Stripe webhooks, file buffers, custom APIs

Example
app.use(express.raw({ type: 'application/octet-stream' }));

Output

Data available as:

req.body  // Buffer

3. express.Router() Function
What it is

Creates a mini Express app

Used for route modularization

Syntax
const router = express.Router();

Why use it?

Clean code

Large projects

Separate routes into files

Example
const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();

router.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.send('User List');
});

module.exports = router;

// app.js
const userRoutes = require('./routes/userRoutes');
app.use('/api', userRoutes);

Output URL
/api/users

4. express.static() Function
What it is

Middleware to serve static files

Syntax
express.static(root, options)

Used For

Serving:

HTML

CSS

JS

Images

Fonts

Example
app.use(express.static('public'));

Folder Structure
public/
 ├── index.html
 ├── style.css
 └── script.js

Access in Browser
http://localhost:3000/index.html

5. express.text() Function
What it is

Middleware to parse plain text request bodies

Syntax
express.text(options)

Example
app.use(express.text());

app.post('/text', (req, res) => {
  res.send(req.body);
});

Content-Type
text/plain

Output
req.body  // string

6. express.urlencoded() Function
What it is

Middleware to parse HTML form data

Syntax
express.urlencoded({ extended: true });

Used For

Form submissions

application/x-www-form-urlencoded

Example
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }));

app.post('/login', (req, res) => {
  console.log(req.body);
  res.send('Form Submitted');
});

HTML Form Example
<form method="POST" action="/login">
  <input name="email" />
  <input name="password" />
  <button type="submit">Login</button>
</form>

Quick Comparison Table
Function	Purpose
express()	Creates Express app
express.raw()	Parses binary data
express.Router()	Modular routing
express.static()	Serves static files
express.text()	Parses plain text
express.urlencoded()	Parses form data
Common Middleware Setup (Real Project)
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

app.use(express.json());
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }));
app.use(express.text());
app.use(express.static('public'));

Viva Tip (Very Important ⭐)

If asked:

Why Express is used?

Answer:

Express is a lightweight Node.js framework used to build fast, scalable backend applications by providing routing, middleware, and HTTP utilities.
